content:
Certainly! Here's an updated HTML and CSS code with some design elements added:

HTML:
```php
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
	<title>Island Escape Game</title>
	<link rel="stylesheet" type="text/css" href="style.css">
</head>
<body>
	<div id="intro-screen">
		<h1>Island Escape Game</h1>
		<p>Players are stranded on an uninhabited island after a shipwreck. They must find a way to escape the island before they die on the island due to exhaustion of resources.</p>
		<button id="start-button" onclick="startGame()">Start Game</button>
	</div>

	<div id="game-screen">
		<!-- Add game elements here -->
	</div>

	<script src="game.js"></script>
</body>
</html>
```
CSS:
```css
body {
	background-color: #bde0c8;
	font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
}

#intro-screen {
	text-align: center;
	margin-top: 100px;
}

#intro-screen h1 {
	font-size: 50px;
	color: #3f3f3f;
}

#intro-screen p {
	font-size: 20px;
	color: #3f3f3f;
	margin-bottom: 50px;
}

#start-button {
	background-color: #3f3f3f;
	color: #ffffff;
	border: none;
	padding: 10px 20px;
	font-size: 20px;
	cursor: pointer;
}

#start-button:hover {
	background-color: #707070;
}

#game-screen {
	display: none;
	background-image: url('island.jpg');
	background-repeat: no-repeat;
	background-position: center center;
	background-size: cover;
	width: 100%;
	height: 100vh;
}
```
In this code, we've added some design elements to the introductory screen and created a new game screen with a background image of an uninhabited island. The `#intro-screen` section includes some basic styles to center the elements on the screen, and the `#game-screen` section adds the island background image and sets the display property to "none" to hide it initially.

You can customize the island image and adjust the styles as desired to create the desired look and feel for your game. I hope this helps!
